          "body": "The chapter opens with a move that is almost without parallel in the ancient Near East: the outgoing judge publicly invites the entire nation to prosecute him. 'Here I am; bear witness against me' (12:3). The challenge is remarkably specific — whose ox, whose donkey, whose bribe (12:3). These are not rhetorical questions; they are legal invitations, the covenant equivalent of a grand jury presentment. The people respond with a triple negative: 'You have not defrauded us or oppressed us or taken anything from any man's hand' (12:4). Samuel then calls the LORD and His anointed as witnesses to the acquittal (12:5). The purpose is not self-congratulation. Samuel's integrity is the moral platform from which the indictment of verses 6-18 can be credibly launched. A prophet who has enriched himself through his office cannot convict a people of their spiritual unfaithfulness. Samuel has no personal stake in what follows — and the people know it. This is the Old Testament pattern for prophetic authority: it is grounded in transparent, publicly verifiable conduct. The New Testament parallel is Paul's identical move in 1 Thessalonians 2:3-10 — 'we never came with flattering speech or a pretext for greed... you are witnesses, and so is God.'"
