          "body": "The chapter's most theologically weighty verse may be 12:22: 'For the LORD will not abandon His people on account of His great name, because the LORD has been pleased to make you a people for Himself.' Samuel does not allow the indictment to be the last word. After the terror (12:18), after the people's confession (12:19), after the acknowledgment that asking for a king was evil (12:19), Samuel says: *do not fear* (12:20). The ground for 'do not fear' is not Israel's contrition but God's name. The LORD's commitment to His people is anchored in His own character and His own elective pleasure — not in their merit, not in their contrition, not even in their obedience to the conditionals of verses 14-15. This is the same theological logic Paul deploys in Romans 11:29: 'the gifts and the calling of God are irrevocable.' It is the same logic that grounds Jeremiah's new covenant promise (Jeremiah 31:31-34): 'I will be their God.' The monarchy changes Israel's political structure; it does not change God's covenantal commitment. He is still Israel's true king even while Saul sits on the throne."
