        "number": 3,
        "title": "The sign that cannot be ignored — creation as covenant witness",
        "range": "12:13-18",
        "excerpt": "Even now, take your stand and see this great thing which the LORD will do before your eyes... So Samuel called to the LORD, and the LORD sent thunder and rain that day.",
        "body": "Verses 13-18 execute the lawsuit's verdict through a sign that moves from verbal argument to physical demonstration. Samuel first acknowledges the irreversibility of the situation: 'here is the king whom you have chosen, whom you have asked for, and behold, the LORD has set a king over you' (12:13). The monarchy is not reversed — it is accepted under new conditions. Then the twin conditionals of verses 14-15 establish the framework under which the monarchy will exist: fear + serve + listen + not-rebel = the LORD is with you; rebel = the LORD's hand against you. The conditionals do not qualify God's grace; they name the covenant's structure.\n\nThe sign of thunder and rain (12:16-18) is calibrated to be maximally impossible to dismiss. Wheat harvest in Palestine ran from late May through June — the height of the dry season. The Gezer Calendar (a tenth-century BC agricultural inscription) confirms that this period was defined by the absence of rain. Samuel does not ask for a minor meteorological anomaly; he asks for a thunderstorm in a season when there were none. The LORD delivers it immediately and unambiguously. The people's reaction — 'greatly feared' (12:18) — is the appropriate response to a direct divine intervention in the natural order.\n\nBut Samuel's stated purpose for the sign is epistemological, not punitive: 'you will know and see that your wickedness is great' (12:17). The thunder is not killing anyone; it is making visible a moral reality that the speech has argued verbally. This is the function of Old Testament signs throughout the canon: the plagues of Egypt are not gratuitous; they demonstrate YHWH's superiority over Egyptian deities who were associated with Nile, darkness, and storm. Here, the rain demonstrates that YHWH commands the weather that Baal was worshiped to control — a pointed rebuke given that verse 10 names Baal-worship as Israel's primary apostasy.\n\nThe people's response in verse 18 ('greatly feared the LORD and Samuel') raises a question of interpretation. Reformed commentators following Calvin have noted that the fear is servile terror, not yet covenantal reverence — the distinction between *timor servilis* and *timor filialis*. Samuel's pastoral response in verse 20 ('do not fear') confirms this: the terror needs to be redirected, not sustained. The sign has done its work in producing conviction; the pastoral task now is to convert conviction into covenant renewal rather than paralysis.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Qol* appears in verse 17 as 'thunder' (literally 'voice' — the voice of the LORD in the storm; cf. Psalm 29) and earlier as 'voice' in verse 1 (Samuel listened to the people's *qol*) and verse 14 (listen to His *qol*). The wordplay is significant: Israel demanded a king by their *qol*; now the LORD speaks His *qol* in thunder to answer. *Yada* (know, v.17) — experiential, embodied knowledge, not merely intellectual. The storm makes them *know* in a way the speech alone could not."
